<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06268154 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06268154 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FREMONT; MAYOR; SUPPORT; PROBE; CITY; EMPLOYEE; TAX; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Fremont Mayor Bill Ball will ask his city council colleagues tonight toapprove the hiring of an independent auditor to investigate the city's failureto withhold millions of dollars in taxes from employee retirement benefitpayments.;   Ball said the move is needed to determine whether the citycommitted fraud. He said he believes the tax problem is the result of anhonest mistake by the city staff.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BALL TO SEEK AUDIT ON TAXESMAYOR SAYS NO COVERUP  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The city has failed to properly reimburse employees for their contributionsto the Public Employees Retirement System -- a mistake that may have resultedin $5 million in unpaid federal taxes over the past three years, city staffreported in a confidential memo to the council three weeks ago.;   Attonight's meeting, Ball will recommend that a council subcommittee of himselfand another council member hire an auditing and accounting firm, without citystaff involvement, to review documents, procedures and correspondence, andinterview current and former city staff members. The firm's report would beavailable to the public.;   &quot;I need the people of this city to know there isno fraud, there is no coverup,&quot; Ball said.;   The firm also would reviewwhether the city is taking the right steps to correct the problem, anddetermine how much the error will cost the city and its employees.;   Themayor said he is angry at Councilman Gary Mello -- who disclosed the problemto the Mercury News -- for saying the city was trying to cover up the taxerror and that city officials may go to jail.;   &quot;The perception is not verygood,&quot; Ball said Monday. &quot;We need to clear the air. If there is somethingwrong, we'll know it. I'm sure there is not, but if there is, we'll know whattook place, who did what and what went wrong.&quot;;   Mello released aconfidential Sept. 3 memo in which city staff and tax attorneys recommendedthe city correct the withholding problem by Jan. 1, but not notify the IRS.;  Last Wednesday, the council decided to negotiate a resolution with the IRS,the Public Employees Retirement System and other public agencies, and tonegotiate with employee unions.;   City Manager Roger Anderman, who returnedMonday from a two-week vacation, named Assistant City Manager Doug Eads tosupervise the negotiations.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DENNIS AKIZUKI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/Am  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910924  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  373  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, September 24, 199100268154,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>